conjecture(flt): no nth power is a sum of two nth powers for n above two

Pierre de Fermat notes in a margin that a^n + b^n = c^n has no positive integer
solution for any n greater than two, claiming a proof too large to fit.

Status: math.conjectured
---
proof(flt-n4): the exponent four, by infinite descent

Fermat proves the one case he left an argument for: no solution for fourth
powers, by descent on a right triangle whose area is a square.

Status: math.proved-informal
---
proof(flt-n3): the exponent three

Euler settles cubes with a descent over the integers adjoined with a cube root
of unity, a step later put on firm ground.

Status: math.proved-informal
Cites: Euler 1770
---
proof(flt-regular-primes): every regular prime exponent

Kummer's theory of ideal numbers proves the conjecture for all exponents that
are regular primes, the first infinite family of cases.

Status: math.proved-informal
Cites: Kummer 1850
---
conjecture(modularity): every rational elliptic curve is modular

The Taniyama-Shimura-Weil conjecture: every elliptic curve over the rationals
arises from a modular form. No visible connection to Fermat yet.

Status: math.conjectured
---
proof(frey-curve): a Fermat solution would build a very strange elliptic curve

Frey observes that a counterexample to Fermat yields a semistable elliptic curve
whose invariants look incompatible with being modular.

Status: math.proved-informal
---
proof(ribet): the Frey curve is not modular, so modularity implies Fermat

Ribet proves Serre's epsilon conjecture: the Frey curve cannot be modular. Hence
if every rational elliptic curve is modular, no Fermat counterexample exists.

Status: math.proved-informal
Depends-On: frey-curve
---
proof(wiles-1993): modularity for semistable elliptic curves

Andrew Wiles announces a proof of the semistable case of modularity, enough,
with Ribet, to settle Fermat.

Status: math.proved-informal
Closes: conjecture:modularity
---
refute(wiles-1993)!: the Euler-system step has a gap

Reviewing the manuscript, Katz finds the Kolyvagin-Flach argument does not bound
the relevant group as claimed. The proof of modularity is incomplete.

Status: math.disproved
Disproves: wiles-1993
BREAKING CHANGE: the 1993 modularity proof is withdrawn; semistable modularity is open again.
---
proof(taylor-wiles): the gap is closed by a Hecke-ring patching argument

Taylor and Wiles replace the broken step with a ring-theoretic patching method,
completing the proof of semistable modularity.

Status: math.proved-informal
Closes: conjecture:modularity
Supersedes: wiles-1993
---
proof(wiles-flt): Fermat's Last Theorem follows from semistable modularity

With semistable modularity proved and Ribet's implication in hand, no Fermat
counterexample can exist. The 358-year-old claim is a theorem.

Status: math.proved-informal
Depends-On: ribet
Depends-On: modularity
Closes: conjecture:flt
---
formalize(flt-lean): a Lean formalization, still in progress

The community FLT project rebuilds the proof in Lean. Much is formalised, but the
development still rests on intermediate results admitted without proof.

Formal-Statement: lean:FLT.fermatLastTheorem
Status: math.open
OPEN: many intermediate results are still admitted as sorry
Depends-On: flt
Cites: Buzzard and collaborators, 2024
